<subSubSection id="ABA834BA0A854DCE1575BFAD3935CEC4" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="C03B20493BBD214BEBE03B8AFD4BC198" lastPageNumber="19" pageNumber="18">
Remarks: Ng (2005c) questioned the utility of the pectoral spine morphology as a useful diagnostic character for 
<taxonomicName id="1B03502C3493BFC31420B476FCB9F1D8" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:085BCF8E-AF07-4A2A-933E-A8FFA5CE820C" class="Actinopterygii" family="Erethistidae" genus="Erethistoides" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Erethistoides Hora 1950:190" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="18" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Erethistoides</taxonomicName>
, noting that some of the serrations on the anterior edge of the pectoral spine in some specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="B0D62ACD021E68FB1857F9C68C062F79" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Erethistes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="filamentosa">Erethistes filamentosa</taxonomicName>
are directed toward the tip of the spine distally (as in 
<taxonomicName id="FBFC18950A637DD56F802D27B5418518" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:085BCF8E-AF07-4A2A-933E-A8FFA5CE820C" class="Actinopterygii" family="Erethistidae" genus="Erethistoides" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Erethistoides Hora 1950:190" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="18" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Erethistoides</taxonomicName>
). Additionally, he identified four apomorphies diagnosing 
<taxonomicName id="006FCD3B3997A50FC2BA704B657B652E" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:085BCF8E-AF07-4A2A-933E-A8FFA5CE820C" class="Actinopterygii" family="Erethistidae" genus="Erethistoides" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Erethistoides Hora 1950:190" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="18" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Erethistoides</taxonomicName>
: 1) neural spines of the first eight postWeberian vertebrae strongly depressed, inflated posteriorly, and depressed in a groove formed by the prezygapophyses of the vertebrae immediately posterior; 2) an enlarged 
<pageStartToken id="2280C4174405CF3A6D86A2211F58DB0F" pageNumber="19">maxilla</pageStartToken>
that is almost as long as the palatine; 3) a fan-shaped mesethmoid lacking distinct cornua (shared with 
<taxonomicName id="30E3B87A6D9972FEB9DF1491C3D338B2" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:8A316B41-E52D-4596-8F18-ED1F5764A35F" class="Actinopterygii" family="Erethistidae" genus="Ayarnangra" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Ayarnangra Roberts 2001:83" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="18" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Ayarnangra</taxonomicName>
); 4) a strongly overhanging snout with premaxillary tooth plate completely exposed when mouth is closed (shared with 
<taxonomicName id="43162309880F9A9A993C63B24219FA31" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:8A316B41-E52D-4596-8F18-ED1F5764A35F" class="Actinopterygii" family="Erethistidae" genus="Ayarnangra" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Ayarnangra Roberts 2001:83" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="18" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Ayarnangra</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="4D39052018C19BB4DB6DD7953F8CD819" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8A3F8B2FD721925E2468F98308EF4174" pageNumber="19">Distribution: Brahmaputra and Meghna drainages, northern India and Nepal (Ng &amp; Edds 2005a).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
